text:
there are those days where you realize, wow, i've changed. the days when you're not quite sure about much except for how grateful you are for everything that has brought you to the point that you're at. i stood up yesterday at the memorial in from of 250-300 ppl and shared from my heart. i had a previous coworker come up and say wow, you never would have done that a year or two ago and i almost got defensive... but then you realize that they are 150% right, no way in heck would i have. i might have felt like i had stuff to say but i never would have had the confidence to do so (that was part of it, he brought toastmasters to the firm and it's helped immensely!), but still, from where i was, how i was, my thought processes, my mental health... to who i am today... don't ever think that you don't have a choice to change. every second is a new opportunity to say you know what? f this. it's been quite the journey to get here, but i'm ready for the good, i'm ready for more growth, i'm ready for what this life wants to test me with next. stronger every single day.
.
.
.
.

text: today @abuseneverbecomesus spoke at "vizhippu: love, power, and relationships" - a conference which aimed to raise awareness about gender-based violence in the tamil community. we spoke about childhood sexual abuse. very happy to have been invited to speak, and many people connected with the team after.  the conference was sponsored/funded by the city of toronto and family services toronto. other topics included gender-based violence in respect to the lgbtq+ identifying persons, elderly population, newcomers,  persons with disabilities, legality, etc. it was great to see the reception from the community, nd to see so many people come out to an event which focused on gender-based violence. #socialcause #socialchange #childhoodsexualabuse #rights #metoo

i felt god say when you look to give hope you will find hope. 
i opened up my journey...not knowing that the decision to do that would connect me to so many facing their own. as i was looking to see light in my own darkness and choosing life...i was not only able to inspire others to see that in their own lives, but i also connected w awesome friends that helped me on my journey as well! i was inspired to create a video to give hope and strength and shine a light on the different journeys we take w lyme...the treatments, tough times, the reality of it, but also the good gifts that come from it too. i wanted to focus on the light in the dark.

text: recently i watched the powerful lorena bobbitt docuseries, and it triggered me to look again at the trauma and ptsd i suffered from experiencing my mom (and myself) be abused by my father for the first about 10 years of my life. my own sister has a hard time understanding what happened as she was too young to remember, and when there is domestic violence in the home, but it is not acknowledged or validated even by many family members- well- it is a wound from which i still openly bleed. the years i performed in the vagina monologues and affiliated with vday- (to stop violence against women), were so healing for me as i would weep over and over at performances that nourished my sad, angry, lost soul. hereâ€™s how i got to california: my mom, dad, sister and i lived in this adorable little house in massachusetts on california avenue. (yes, synchronicity!) we seemed like a picture perfect family from the outside, as many dysfunctional homes do. inside our home though, it was pure torture. i lived in a near constant state of anxiety. my father was an addict, a womanizer, a gambler, an untreated bipolar person, a checked out father, and a toxic individual that also had charm and intellect and charisma, and abilities to make one feel both on top of the world, and like a piece of shit. my mother, although had her own issues, was such an amazingly strong and loving soul. she was a great parent in spite of the circumstances. she was forgiving and patient, and wanted to keep our family together despite how much pain and suffering my dad brought. after 10 years of intense verbal abuse, pushing my mom around physically, threatening her life, and continuing to come home drunk and dark, the tiny and brave being that i was got so fearful one night that dad would seriously hurt my precious mom in the middle of an intense fight i was witness to, that i went to the phone and dialed 911. i got scared when someone answered that my dad would hear me and freak out, so i hung up. but i had watched enough tv to know the cops would still come. from our testimonies and the evidence, the police determined my father needed to be arrested. he was taken away in cuffs.(cont. in comments)

circe, by madeline miller
genre: fiction, greek mythology, fantasy
ğŸƒ
a story of greek gods, myths and magic. the centre to this novel is circe, the sorceress and daughter of helios. she was able, by means of drugs and incantations, to change humans into wolves, lions, and swine.
ğŸƒ
when circe discovers her powers, she commits a wicked act and is then banished to an island. what follows then is an account of her life on this island. there isnâ€™t a plot, but a series of many incidents and how multiple gods, mortals and myths are weaved into her life. the narrative is very compelling and keeps you hooked right till the end.
ğŸƒ
to me this book was a psychological analysis of a women. the character of circe is so endearing. she is aware about her powers and that she  isnâ€™t the greatest. she faces ostracism, insult, abuse and more hate... yet she has streaks of humility and sympathy. she continues to take control of her destiny and define her life. i definitely donâ€™t take this as a weakness of women, but rather her power to engulf all the negativity and still be steady, resilient and empathetic. however i wished the author showed an equal balance of aggression in circeâ€™s character. there was action, i expected slightly more.
ğŸƒ
while this may be about gods, there is a lot of humanity in there. it makes you realise the mortality of humans. through daedalusâ€™s character, author symbolises the satisfaction one gets by creating their own things, doing things by hands rather by the powers of magic.
ğŸƒ
the narrative is very relevant and strikes a chord with many things of our world today - the gap between powerful and powerless, ugly nature of politics, the way the women are treated and revelations with #metoo ... and more. clearly a reader can read it at many different levels.
ğŸƒ
simple story, powerful narrative, poetic and engaging throughout... must read. taking one star away because i wished there was a bit more writing about other characters.
ğŸƒ
rating: 4/5
ğŸƒ

text:
.
yesterday someone who i use to be very close with said something unspeakable to me.
.
to say i was shocked is an understatement.
.
in the past i would have accepted those words as truth. i would have allowed them to affect me. i would have internalized those words and fixated on them.
.
not anymore. iâ€™ve learned a few things over the past couple of years:
.
1. peopleâ€™s words only affect you in so much as you let them. you have the power to reject negativity from others. you donâ€™t have to accept it.
.
2. verbal abuse and negativity is usually more a reflection of an internal struggle of the person who said them than you.
.
3. forgiveness is non- negotiable.
.
4. fighting my battles (especially those of the mind) are always won when fought in christ.
.
5. i am worthy and so are you. no one has a right to disrespect us!
.
6. i matter. my voice matters. you matter. your voice matters. you have a right and responsibility to use it. donâ€™t let others silence you! your voice and your journey are your power.
.

text:
recovery part 2
iâ€™ve never been one to share my #transformation journey.. 1. because itâ€™s not a very traditional one, and 2. recovery images can be a trigger factor for many who are battling for their own freedom and peace... with that being said, please read to understand â™¥ï¸
#anorexia became a hidden blessing in mylife, at least that is how i am choosing to accept it as. developing anorexia was a path i subconsciously became exposed to, do to a deeper trauma of being sexually abused as a child. as i stated in my last post about this, i had no recollection or even the slightest idea that i would be saying #metoo 21 years after it happened. 
my reason for sharing my story is to show to others that #recovery is 100% possible! iâ€™ve spent 21 years of my life surviving every chapter of my book.. and just now, at 25 i am able to say i am living and truly experiencing my life.  the first two photos are of myself at age 17.. when the disorder was truly taking a toll on my body(iâ€™m not giving detailed numbers because again, trigger factor). i recall breathing being painful.. i recall many sleepless nights wondering if i was going to wake up the next day. i recall hell. 
the third post, is a video that i did a couple days ago! choosing my heart beat over an unreachable idea of what â€œperfectionâ€ is supposed to be, will forever be the best decision i have ever made. recovery is a choice, and itâ€™s a lot of hard work... itâ€™s painful and at times, excruciatingly unbearable.. but! the light always shines through after a wall gets knocked down. choosing your eating disorder over your body, mind and spirit.. is also agonizingly painful.. however, there will never be any light ahead. in the end, it all comes down to which pain youâ€™d rather go through. both paths suck, but only one comes with the rewards of self love, and the freedom we all deserve. 7 years are between the photos and the video... i became ill at age 14. it has taken me a total of 11 years to fully recover, inside and out! recovery is different for everyone. start choosing recovery minute by minute. hour by hour.. day by day. do what you can and forgive yourself every step of the way. much love to all the warriorsâ™¥

text: years ago, i used to work for this awesome little newspaper in la that got bought by some young billionaire. couple weeks into the job we hear there is some other newspaper owner billionaire from sm coming to visit the douche bag billionaire who bought our paper. our new owner was excited to show off his new acquisition so he kept bugging us about pushing out some pch traffic news alert so that he could show off to his billionaire buddy. in his haste, he forwards this back and forth he had with his buddy. both of them considered themselves democrats and voted for clinton, and one of them even sat on the aclu board in la. this was the day i realized that no matter the party, the difference between us (the owned) and them (the owners) is that we will always be less than human to these "people." #metoo #berniesanders #newbourgeoisie #wealthworship #moneyworship

text:
before the adam and eve story, humanity did not know shame.

shame is not a natural human instinct.

although children are born with all kinds of other instincts that could be considered 'sinful', shame is not one of them. we lie as kids, we cheat. we need to be taught fairness and sharing. but shame? no. shame is not inherent in our make-up. no child is born with shame. it is only when an adult shames a child that shame becomes part of his/her understanding of his/herself. shame is given. shame is taught. shame is applied. shame is projected. shame only comes from the outside.

historically, it was when the introduction of the abrahamic religions started to make their way across the world that this shame concept became a part of our collective story.
.

what is shame exactly? shame is the concept that something is 'inherently sinful' or 'wrong' about our bodies, about ourselves.

in the adam and eve story, the couple disobeyed the almighty god and was banished from paradise and cursed with shame. cursed with the story that something is sinful about their bodies, sexuality and pleasure centers. eve and all her descendants would be cursed with pain in childbirth. (which coincidentally, women who carry a lot of shame have the most painful birth experiences. women who are less tied to shame have the orgasmic birth experiences we hear about.) because of these religions, shame was now part of the human experience.

before this, humanity had no concept that our bodies are somehow defective, disgusting, sinful and should be hidden, private, seperate. in fact, when you look at the archeological evidence, it shows that humanity felt quite the opposite... we celebrated, loved and enjoyed nudity, sex and our bodies. it can be seen across many ancient cultures. the female body was especially elevated as a divine experience. nakedness and sex were part of spirituality. sacred union was how you could experience god.

so shame is not a human condition. it is a story we've adapted. a very powerful story. a story that makes us give over our inner power to an outer authority figure. it's no wonder... continued in comments...

text:
"much better together"
a plant love shirt ! this definitely was on my posting list. but it was hard to do a selfie that shows the hole quote.
i will start school again in summer and i'm super excited. i want to catch up my highschool graduation wich i wasn't able to finish because i had problems with my classmates and teachers and with my mental health. my goal is to go to university.
.
.
what to do if you get bullied:

if you already have problems with  your mental health you should look for a therapist or better for a psychiatrist. they will support you with some konversationen and maybe medicine. sounds a bit wierd but it really helped me with my stabilisation. because the world seems different if you are depressed and the  metabolism in your brain don't work like it should. the result of the stabilisation is that you don't colabate so often, mentally.
and you should eventually think about changing your environment.
at least it helps to try some skills. these are tepts like hot, cold, spicy, bitter, warm, smells etc ,that counteract to your mental strain and other skills are things you like to do  and make you happy. i recommend to write a list with them. it helps to make you feel better and let your self worth feeling grow through your successful experiences. be proud to be who you are. and let them talk. it is also important to clear some missunderstandings. but sometimes you just have to let them talk. because not everyone understands if he is acting wrong. something important at the end:  don't do anything that harms you to handle your problems. like drinking alcohol and /or taking other drugs or hurt your self for purpose in any other way. it may take away the pain for a few hours or so but never the less it will only make it worse.

text:
before you start with the similarities between mj and r kelly - one is alive and can defend himself and if convicted can be jailed for his crime, while the other is dead and his legacy can only be ruined. â£
â£
oprah is catching backlash for this interview but i can't comment until i see it in it's entirety. â£
â£
the audience was full of approx. 100 sex abuse survivors, so the deck was stacked against jackson and before the interview started, these 100 survivors, sat through the 4 hour, documentary. then oprah conducted the interview.  that's like having vegans watch 4 hrs of cows getting slaughtered and then trying to serve them a burger.  i suspect this is where the backlash is stemming from. â£
â£
winfrey, a known advocate for victims of child sexual abuse reached out to reed via email after seeing the film and said,â£
â£
'dan, you were able to illustrate in these four hours what i've tried to explain in 217.  this moment transcends michael jackson."â£
â£
both men depicted in the film said the michael jackson molested them.  safechuck who was a child commercial star, says that his molestation started at the age of 10, and robson says he was molested between the ages of 7 - 14. â£
â£
both men previously testified on behalf of jackson during a separate child molestation trial, which the jackson estate and family frequently point to as proof that the men are now lying.â£
â£
the man behind the film, reed, addressed the family and estate's criticism of the fact that he did not include their perspective in leaving neverland.â£

text:
how are you bridging the differences between yourself and others? âœ’ğŸ–¤
@thewordforthis

i really love this simple, relevant, accessible statement by @constancewu. we each bring our own experiences and perspectives to this work; thatâ€™s a given, and perfectly natural. but my goal here has always been to create a space where not only are we connected by our shared experiences, but where our differences are the subject of curiosity, compassion, and connection.

and so itâ€™s my responsibility to do more than just be passively open: actively working to educate myself on the countless ways our experiences are shaped by factors like race, national and cultural origins, economics, religion, physical and mental health, body type, family dynamicsâ€¦ all of it.

our access to this platform itself is a privilege, an advantage that makes us different. it can be overwhelming and extremely uncomfortable to acknowledge all of this, let alone take action to begin to change it (or even figure out what action to take). but acknowledging it without defensiveness or fear is a good first step.

this scene was so incredibly powerful. the way that this amazing show handles these topics with delicacy and grace completely blows me away. this episode had the perfect balance of comedy and coverage,, coverage being on a topic that is so important. the storyline in the episode was so important to be seen on tv and to have seen it was so astounding. it was completely breathtaking in every possible way and for every possible reason. the way that each scene was constructed to create this incredible storyline that illustrated so many different things: jake being an incredible ally (in this scene and many others), this conversation/debate between rosa and amy, the entire storyline and all of the issues it brought up about the world we live in: two steps forward one step back. the talent shown from all of the actors was awe-inspiring and sensational, @melissafumero â€˜s acting in this scene had me speechless and teary. i am so proud of @stephaniebeatriz for having her directorial debut be on something so gravitational and powerful and she has absolutely done the #metoo movement proud. i love this show with my whole heart and this episode encapsulates so many reasons why. and to nbc for airing an episode about this topic: thank you thank you thank you!!!!!

text:
i live in constant fear of men.

as some of you know, i recently moved to india. and to be honest, iâ€™m not really enjoying it so far. apart from the pollution and the jam-packed streets, i am really disappointed in society as a whole. every day, when i go outside, the watchman under my building eyes me with wretched hunger in his eyes. his greasy smile frightens me to the extent that i am not willing to come outside the house. today, when i was crossing the street, one man passed me on a motorcycle and smirked at me. a woman (presumably his wife) was sitting behind him. he didnâ€™t even have the dignity to hide his smirk when a woman was sitting behind him. another man whistled as he cycled past me. every day, i go outside to be play. yesterday, my friends asked me to ask the guys if we could play with them. â€œhey, we want to play with you, too,â€ i said to one boy. his reply was repeating what i said mockingly and telling me to â€œask him nicely.â€ when my friend did ask him nicely, he said no. another friend was telling me about her boyfriend. he seemed like a major dick, and i told her so. she replied, â€œat least he doesnâ€™t hit me.â€ when i got angry at this she said, â€œthis is india.â€ when i go outside i make sure iâ€™m wearing modest clothes. not because anyone from my family asks me to or because of the societal pressures. because i am so sick of being catcalled, being touched, being undressed with othersâ€™ eyes. there are countless incidents that happen to me and every other woman. i am so tired of being objectified in such a disgusting way. i am barely a woman; iâ€™m only sixteen. i am desperate to get out of this country. and no, i am not saying india is the only country this happens in, but the frequency of harassment here is astronomical. and that is why i say, i live in constant fear of men.
.
p.s. this piece is very raw and unrefined, and iâ€™m not even sure if i could call it poetry. writing is the only way i pour out my emotions so here it is.
.
.
.
.

text:
**link in profile to learn more and submit your act of courage** when i was living in new york city, i saw a woman who i causally knew being verbally harassed by a tough-looking man. acting without thinking too much, i went to her side, greeted her enthusiastically, and quickly walked her away. the guy was surprised, but slowly followed us. soon i ushered her through a doorway that led to the busy kitchen of a chinese restaurant with several cooks, to whom i explained that we were seeking sanctuary. the tough man didn't enter; she and i waited until he walked away from the door. she and i held hands until she calmed down, and we left through the front door and into the sunshine.

i canâ€™t believe i managed to miss the buzz around â€˜cat personâ€™ - the short story about modern dating that taps into the #metoo movement - before listening to kristen roupenian on how to fail with @elizabday . this is a great interview, particularly when the conversation discusses the difficulties around womenâ€™s writing often mistaken for being autobiographical, or cathartic for the writer, instead of a creative process like any other. the story itself is dark, and perhaps becomes even darker in that we can all recognise the thought processes of margot, and her friends, as the story builds. itâ€™s a compelling and unsettling story and well worth googling, if you havenâ€™t read it - although i suspect i may be the last person to this particular party! ğŸ™ˆ

text:
hurt people hurt other people
when one is hurt the usual feeling is that no one can understand how they feel. sometimes you feel inflicting that same pain you feel on another person to feel better.  the truth is that your flesh may feel good for a while but depending on the condition of your heart and soul, depending on how seared your soul from god and guilt will be the prevailing condition 
sometimes we even make it a habit that it becomes a character. that is not the will of god for us. god expects us to overcome evil with good, hate with love and hurt with joy. when we are hurt we are to bring joy to the lives of those around us that are also hurting. the bible says love as you love yourself but we forget that before jesus went to glory he gave us a higher commandment saying we should love others as he has loved us. god bless you as you do so. one love one god one way.

text:
at #sophiamurielflemmingreads, i know that w.e.b dubois described it best: black folks and double consciousness. 
that is one main aspect that comes into my mind as a black woman. dubois described double consciousness for black folks as having two identities: one of race and one of nation. being black and being american...but not being able to be full american because of our race not being accepted. 
at the time, when the constitution, declaration of independence, and other u.s. documents are written/drafted/created, it was in the context for white males who were slave owners, property owners, and even owners of the families that they inherited and/or created.

through a black feminist womanist lens, it is important for me to see what these documents were meant for. however, what the founding fathers may not have realized completely is that black slaves were black folks and black folks would be freedâ€”not freed under the best circumstances, but we were. 
now, it is our time to continue amending these documents and use these documents that all people will operate in the realm of freedom. itâ€™s also black womenâ€™s time and other women of colorâ€™s time to be recognized for our past and present achievements that will launch a better future for the upcoming generations in our country.

#sophiamurielflemmingreads #sophiamurielflemmingswrites

text_retweet:
if people knew the dark truth behind elephant tourism, would they still visit a temple elephant, go on that ride, or take that selfie?

this picture shows the truth behind captive elephants. this 'crush box' is the process in which elephants are domesticated and trained. they're forced into a cage-like structure and tied so they're unable to move. they're beaten for 23 hours of the day, deprived of sleep, and starved until the elephant's spirit is completely broken and therefore will accept chains and obey the commands of man. it's a very brutal and disturbing process.

the good news? we, as consumers, have the power to change this! share this post with a friend.

text:
i forgive myself. for i once was a demon.
spawn of temptation programmed by media.
at the age of six i lost my innocence. 
engulfed by the sensation of a deceitful  stare of connection and euphoria.
.
blue eyed, blonde angel touching herself within a movie theater. nothing but white gloves caressing her entire body. i lost my ability to be truly  present with women through this one experince.
.
.
i was hooked, like a crack addict on rock. everything became about wanting to experince this disulisionment from there until i found myself again. .
.
television novelas where the most beautiful surrendered to the most masculine men. boastful and materialistic idols influenced who i thought i had to be. .
.
i can boldly admit this made my hand wander from time to time. early teens was a shameful period of shadows and blue screen portals of lust. .
.
 i found a relationship young. which allowed me to explore these cravings even deeper. spilling youthful energy rather then harnessing the sacredness of union.
.
.
conintuation next post ...
.
.

text:
gofundme deadline tomorrow!

sunday 3rd march - that gives time for us to transfer money to freetown with enough time to process everything. donate at:

http://www.gofundme.com/becomeempowered

thank you so much to everyone who has already donated so far, we have hit Â£600 of our Â£1000 goal! we can make it!! every Â£10 donation is a school girl in sierra leone having access to travel, food and training at our 1 day event designed around women's empowerment.

training will cover education, health, self esteem and entrepreneurship in response to the hands off our girls campaign by the first lady, and the #nationalstateofemergency of #genderbasedviolence and #rape in sierra leone, recently announced by the president.

we're doing a #gofundme campaign to launch this #becomeempowered #womensempowerment event in partnership with the patriotic advocacy network in freetown sierra leone on #internationalwomensday - 8th march.

we're trying to reach 100 girls (capacity for the venue) from different schools around freetown to let them know we see them, we're behind them, and we want to practically help by empowering them with the tools to create physical, mental and emotional action and support groups in their communities

please share with your communities

#handsoffourgirls #16daysofactivism #protectourgirlsnow #metoo #hearmetoo #enoughisenough #respectwomen #fgm #sexualviolence #becomensf #patrioticadvocacynetwork #freetown #sierraleone #salone #fgm

text:
it took 6+ months of court dates, trying to serve someone who doesn't want to be found, learning that you can now serve people electronically via social media thanks to a top notch legal student, finally being awarded a protection from abuse order, figuring out who could enforce the order once it was received, compiling the evidence and drafting a letter to the website (plus so many other roadblocks and headaches and straight up ridiculousness along the way that i won't get into)... but, tonight it is with great pleasure that i tell you it was all worth it. yesterday, i received word from the deputy sheriff that  liam carleton photography's flickr account is finally shut down, once and for all. no more sharing images of models without their consent (on that platform). this is one small victory for so many women who have been harmed by this man's actions. it doesn't even begin to suffice as restitution for the all the harm he's inflicted on his collaborators, but it's a step in the right direction. hopefully this action makes it more difficult for him to operate moving forward. i won't stop until we've contacted every platform he uses.

text:
â€œthe me too movementâ€
an outtake from the â€œcutting up in the barbershopâ€ podcast discussion at @fly_nerds_chop_shop @jconquer1 
bill cosby was sentenced to three to ten years in prison for a sexual assault. his conviction marked the rise of the #metoo movement as well as the downfall of an african-american icon. was bill dealt a bad hand as a black man? was race a factor in cosbyâ€™s case? 
the playing field is not leveled for blacks in america in the eyes of justice and society. history tells us that black men who are accused of raping white women have often been lynched. history tells us that black men who face the american justice system are disproportionately incarcerated. history tells us that cosby, a black man, had little chance of walking away from the accusations of dozens of mostly white women.

text:
can we please urge men to not sexually assault women? can we teach everyone the definition of #consent?

consent is defined in canada's criminal code in s. 273.1(1), as the voluntary agreement to engage in the sexual activity in question. the law focuses on what the person was actually thinking and feeling at the time of the sexual activity.

and yes, we know #notallmen. also, if this post offends you share your comments with your therapist, not here.

text:
march is #endometriosisawareness month
.
just a few statistics:
- 1 in 10 women are diagnosed with endometriosis.
- 80% of women have difficulties carrying out tasks during their period because of pain.
- 70% of people suffering from ptsd have been victims to physical assault, rape or abuse. - around 77% of the victims are women.
.
.
i just spent an inspiring weekend surrounded by women working in menstrual cycle awareness. talking about women empowerment, our inner strength and wisdom, how to access it and the hurdles that have to be climbed to step into our power.
.
one big topic is menstrual health and how many women are suffering from immense pain every month. a fact that rather disconnects us from our source, our womb.
.
for nearly ten years iâ€™ve been suffering from endometriosis. iâ€™ve been admitted to hospital several times before being diagnosed, iâ€™ve had two surgeries praying every single time to wake up and still being able to have children.
iâ€™ve been crawling to my bag to reach for painkillers uncountable nights not being able to stand up because of the unbearable pain. i literally hated and resented this time of the month, i hated my cycle. .

looking at the numbers of sexual abuse in women and at the numbers of women suffering from immense menstrual pain, the link is undeniable.

text:
national eating disorder awareness week is coming to a close. i usually post something around this time about how happy i am to be â€œrecoveredâ€, which is true, but the reality of recovery for me is a lot messier and more fraught than a before and after picture can convey. 
i dislike my body 75% of the time. i hate the way it looks and feels and behaves. even after years of therapy and self work, my body still feels like a stranger to me.

a lot of my disorder was about regaining some semblance of control over a body that felt stolen from me by multiple instances of sexual assault, constant medical issues, and bipolar disorder. food was my way of regaining ownership.

instead of using food to love myself, i used it as punishment. i played out self hatred through starvation, binging and purging, and vitriolic self talk. i was mean to my body for 9 years, which is a huge chunk of my life.

after two recovery centers, countless therapy sessions, and finding medication that works, i came out on the other side kind of uncertain of who i was without my disorder. 
climbing became a way for me to get to know myself again, for me to feel every emotion imaginable, and to feel at home in my body. being outside with friends, moving over rock, and every now and then doing something iâ€™m proud of has been life bringing.

i am working on loving my body at rest as much as i do when i am moving. it is unspeakably difficult, but i am trying. i am also trying to find self worth beyond performance, which is aided by having deep love for a few humans and an animal.

i am not perfect in recovery. my brain still autopilots toward calorie counting, eating a donut is a monumental feat, and i have had panic attacks at grocery stores and restaurants when faced with deviating from safe foods. but, iâ€™m proud of all iâ€™ve accomplished, because 25% of the time i do love myself, and itâ€™s one of the best feelings on earth.

i was nervous about posting this and i felt pretty self conscious posing for this picture, but hey, hereâ€™s to diving head first into discomfort and nudging myself closer to 100%. #neda #nedaweek #nedawareness #girlswhoclimb #wildandweightless #edrecovery #climbing #metoo

text:
alexandria ocasio-cortez was born into a puerto rican family in the bronx, new york city, new york. while in college, ocasio-cortez became an intern in the immigration office and evidently was the only spanish speaker at the age of 19-20. as a result she was the lifeline for loved ones calling in looking for family members who had been grabbed by ice. â €
â €
ocasio-cortez graduated cum laude from boston university's college of arts and sciences in 2011, majoring in international relations and economics. after graduating, ocasio-cortez moved back to the bronx and began working as an educational director. she also began working as a bartender and waitress to help her mother.â €
â €
after working as an organizer for bernie sanders's 2016 presidential campaign ocasio-cortez travelled across america speaking to those affected by the flint water crisis and the dakota access pipeline. through this experience she was inspired to start work in her own community. in 2017 ocasio-cortez decided it was time for change. between shift work she went out canvassing for her congressional campaign. in june of 2018 ocasio-cortez was elected over joe crowley ending his 10-year term. â €
â €
above all that she is a fierce leader and is not afraid to stand up for herself or others. i canâ€™t wait to see whatâ€™s to come with her!â €
â €

text:
a day care worker was charged with child abuse after a video showed her throwing a 3-year-old girl across the room

the little girl was hospitalized and needed several stitches for a deep gash on her forehead, her family's attorney said.

video showing wilma brown throwing a 3-year-old girl across the room at a day care center.

two day care workers in missouri were charged with child abuse on thursday after surveillance videos showed them injuring young children in their care.

wilma brown, 27, was charged after a video showed her throwing a 3-year-old girl into furniture at the brighter day care and preschool in pine lawn on feb. 1. 
an attorney for the victim's family provided a copy of the video to the media.

the little girl who is not being identified suffered from a serious head injury, the police said in a facebook post.

the girl had to be hospitalized after her injury got infected, according to the family's attorney, jennifer hansen.

the child also had facial swelling and needed stitches for a deep gash on her forehead, hansen told the media on friday. the incident has "emotionally taken a toll on her," she added.

ariana silver, another employee at the day care, was also charged with child abuse in relation to a separate incident on feb. 4 in which a 4-year-old child under her care was injured, police said. that incident was also captured on video but the footage has not been released. police did not provide additional details about the incident.

hansen said that the family could not speculate why brown would hurt the child, who appeared to be "calm and contained" in the minutes leading up to the incident. "it's such a terrible thing to do to a child," hansen said.

in the day care's "unintentional injury form", brown wrote that the child had "bumped her head" when she fell on a carpet on feb. 1.

brown's alleged actions only came to light five days after the incident, when the girl's parents asked to review surveillance footage at the day care.

the little girl had been going to the brighter day care and preschool every day for about a year.

police arrested brown on friday

to learn more visit legalactionnews.com

text:
good morning! today is day 2 of the #marchmeetthemaker challengeâ™¡ day 2 is, how you started. this is scary for me to share, but here i go.
â™¡
13 years ago, my next door neighbor had offered help watching over me and my sister for my dad (who is a single father and worked often to support us). she was a avid crafter (especially when it came to yarn!). i remember how fascinated i was with the beautiful things she made (specifically the gorgeous doll dresses she made). so one day i asked her to teach me and she did! the rest was history from there! i no longer speak to her because her husband sexually abused me (sorry if hearing that is triggering for some) but despite it all i am happy we crossed paths because she had taught me something that even 13 years later i'm still very passionate about.  i'm grateful to have at least walked away from that situation with more than just trauma and negative emotions
ğŸ™Œâ™¡

text: the normalization of child sex abuse perpetuates the problem! listening to viola davis describe the moment that changed the trajectory of her sister's life was heartbreaking. the one sentence that replays on a loop in our minds is, "leave that man alone, he does that to all of the little girls". that one statement explains the pervasiveness of sexual abuse in our communities and how children are left unprotected because so many refuse to label the behavior exactly what it is - a crime. millions of children have been victimized and millions more are at risk because the adults around them consider these behaviors "normal" because they've seen it happen so frequently and the victims are made to feign normalcy afterwards so the abuser isn't made to be held accountable for their crime and the family doesn't have to confront the issue and the possible fallout that would result from doing so. but, it's time to end this normalization of sex abuse. if you see something, say something. say it loudly and boldly. we have to save the children! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #church #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #socialmedia

text:
introducing our speakers 
tanushree dutta
team tedxcvs is thrilled to announce its far away on-screen speaker, tanushree datta. 
hailing from a conservative hindu bengali family, she worked her way into the industry by pursuing her dream of modelling. 
a model as well as an actress, she has been the recipient of femina miss india universe title 2004. 
being the catalyst to the "#metoo" movement in india by voicing her story of sexual harassment, she is regarded as one of the most fearless and boldest female icon in our industry.

she has been a feminist role model for women who have been reluctant to speak out against harassment and has inspired thousands of young girls to be forthcoming. 
we cannot be more excited to hear about her life story. .
.

text: if you trust god and walk with him faithfully, god will allow your eyes to witness visibly, what he speaks to your heart spiritually. god gave me a unique word in 2010 declaring to me that we were stepping into the â€œyear of the womanâ€. i meditated on that interesting word at the time and preached a two part series on it. i then began to realize that it was more than just a â€œyearâ€ as i knew it but actually an age. i remember being so nervous when god gave me the message. i had so many thoughts. i felt so unqualified as a man to speak about what god told me he was doing with women. how would the men respond? would a message about women be alienating? would it be received at all? i preached the series anyway and moved on but held those truths in my heart and from that time forward never looked at women the same. for context this was years before #metoo and we were just at the tip of any serious conversation about the executive-level inclusion of women in the workplace. fast forward to today, having just wrapped a 7 city tour with my peerless bride @sarahjakesroberts, our daughters @itsreallyren and @teyaahunter and our spiritual daughters @tinawatkinsquaye @dananecole @lizzykay1 @visionsent_kayla, sister @cjakescoleman (and many other incredible women and men) and witnessing thousands of women be empowered toward their highest identity and commanded to evolve in that identity is just surreal. who would have thought that that word would play itself out right in front of my eyes through the vision of the woman that i decided to give my heart to. itâ€™s absolutely overwhelming! honey, congratulations on you stepping into your calling, your willingness to evolve and growing your own wings and through doing so, now having the capacity and anointing to give multitudes of women theirs. you are a gift to this world! i love you and am cheering/championing you on in your great call. @womanevolve

text:
i have been sitting on this post for a long, long time. i don't know why, but it just kept coming to my mind and heart that i need to share this story. i've thought about it. i've wrestled with it. i've prayed about it. i've lost sleep over it. i've been inspired by others who have put their personal journeys out there. i need to put mine out there for me, and if it helps just one person then it will be worth it. .
from the time i was 7 until i was 10 i was sexually abused by a neighbor. this is something that 99% of people in my life do not know about me. it isn't something i dwell on, but it is something that affects me every day. i don't think therapy was as much of a widely talked about thing when i was younger, so after the man was put in jail we just went on with our lives as if it never happened. i feel like i've dealt with it pretty well, but there are still times where i feel guilty for not telling someone, my heart will start racing out of nowhere, or i get panicky for my children. it will always be there. but i don't have to let it define who i am. i choose not to be a victim. i am a survivor. and i am thriving. i know there are so many women out there who have a history of abuse who are not, though, and my heart aches for them. .
1 in 5 girls is a victim of sexual abuse. let that sink in. one in five! if you are one of those girls, please know that you are not alone. you don't have to be ashamed, and suffer in silence like i did for so many years. talking about it is empowering and freeing. i never wanted anyone to feel sorry for me or give me that pitying look. i didn't want to be different or seen as "that girl," so i never talked about it. what if i have other women in my life who feel the same and can benefit from knowing my story and that they are not alone? that is why i am speaking out. because, whoever you are, you are not alone! i am here for you and with you, and together we are strong.

comic- the mundanity hurts - vol.1
.
tw: sexual violence .
so. iâ€™ve had this comic series brewing for a while. months. months and months. itâ€™s been something iâ€™ve wanted to do for a really long time if iâ€™m honest. but i didnâ€™t know how it would be received, and i wasnâ€™t sure i was ready for the fallout of posting content like this online. but i am now. .

so here it is. the first volume of my very imperfect, (intentionally so,) very personal comic illustration series, the mundanity hurts. everything in these comic illustrations will be real. 
i will always post the trigger warnings, if i miss any please let me know. 
i will still continue to post my other work, portraits and tattoo designs etc, but this is just something that i have to finally share. itâ€™s the more obvious story telling element to my work that has been itching at me for a while. 
please remember this series is in no way meant to be the best example of my artwork, style or techniques. 
iâ€™ll be posting these once a week or so, or at steady intervals between my other work. 
iâ€™m hoping the content in here will help in some very minuscule way towards helping anyone who has been through anything similar feel less isolated. .

text:
we proudly are partners with @safechr. here's more about about our them:
#safechr is a volunteer based, clinician led and survivor empowered grassroots organization that was formed in 2013 and registered in march 2014 after a group of survivorsâ€™ felt their voices were unheard during a panel presentation in 2013. the goal is to ensure that their voices are heard throughout the globe. realizing the need for survivors to be the driving force in all that we do in combating human trafficking a paradigm shift was created in 2013 and is reflected in all our programs. since then, safechr has hosted four conferences at the national level and formed partnerships with organizations around the country to assist victims of human trafficking with placement, treatment, and rehabilitation. in this country we have between 100,000 to 300,000 victims and barely 2000 beds available creating enormous difficulties with placement and rehabilitation. Â the treatment program will be the implementation of a c-safe iris program run by clinicians with long histories of program development experience and in working with csec victims, survivors - Â assisted by victim advocates. .
.
.

text:
behind the mirror 
this art piece shows the circumstances faced by a rape victim in our society . hearts of people are with victim but the tongues are on against. people use to blame the victim , they abuse the victim and her family and also encourages the evils by supporting them (no evidence or victim of rape) ..nowadays the justice is like a pearl found in the dark and deep sea. 
every rape victim is behind the mirror someday we will definetly bring them in front of mirror.

text: did you know that emotional trauma affects our physical health? 1 year ago today, i called my sexual assault by name for the first time, after 4 years of suppressing it. god brought it to light after leading at a redemption group immersion at church. it was a saturday night, and i physically shook until wednesday, finally allowing myself to acknowledge and feel what had happened to me. rape culture taught me that it was my fault. i remembered thinking â€œi put myself in this situation, itâ€™s my fault,â€ i remember thinking it wasnâ€™t assault because i was too smart and strong to let that happen. (taking the blame makes you feel a little less powerless). what i realized is that being sexually assaulted says nothing about my character, my intelligence, or my strength. i had already known this, and spent years counseling other girls in this way, but had never allowed it for myself. the lord reminded me a year ago that i didnâ€™t hate physical touch (in fact, the opposite) until that night. he has redeemed it back for me in so many ways this last year, i even find myself craving it again like i used to. (unless a man i donâ€™t know/trust tries to touch me, then i still get nauseous) i know now that this assault is connected to a medical flare that landed me in bed for 6 weeks shortly after, because emotional release was a huge part of my medical treatment last year. my body literally trembled for days last year when i realized how powerless it felt for my multiple verbal â€œnoâ€™sâ€ to be questioned and ignored. and it took men and women forming a literal circle around me, praying, and telling me i was safe for the shaking to stop. iâ€™ve been very selective who iâ€™ve shared this with since, i still find it hard to say it out loud, but it was a huge part of my healing to intentionally work through my trauma, so iâ€™m talking about it now. i wrote more about it, months ago, and when iâ€™m ready, ill share it. for now, just know that even if youâ€™ve never told anybody, years later, you can still talk about it now. tell someone. tell me. tell someone. and also? it wasnâ€™t your fault.

text:
i've already been a #metoo victim once at work i thought i could know if that would happen again and stop it immediately but here i was last week wanting to kill myself as i could not bare the idea of going back to work and face that guy. lucky for me i am surrounded by wonderfull people and professionals that advised me to talk about it to my manager. that man looked at me and said he would stop it right ahead that the other guy was an asshole and that could not keep going. last night i slept like i haven't slept in weeks. i'm also medicated to prevent anxiety rush. 
if i'm talking about that here it's because i know how freaking hard this can be. when you feel too low, seek for help. you think you are a hopeless case nothing or no one can help you but some people can and will. don't pass your pain to your loved ones. heal it. (saying that but i'm not done with pain myself ^^) is just one person reads this and feels like life is  too much to bear  please please go seek professional advice â¤
#autism #asperger #work #depression #suiciadalthoughts #suicide #howtokillmyself #harrasment #sexualharassment

text:
vinta nanda reacts on the news of alok nath playing judge in film around #metoo

a news report that actor alok nath is playing a judge pronouncing a sentence against a child molester in a forthcoming film has left writer-director vinta nanda, who has accused him of rape, speechless. â€œi donâ€™t know what to say. when i heard about this ironical casting my mind, my heart and soul was with wing commander varthaman abhinandan. i couldnâ€™t keep my eyes off the television screen because i wanted to see him as he stepped on indian soil today,â€ vinta said emotionally.

her mindspace is currently taken up with the violence at the border. â€œiâ€™m praying for peace and wishing that the almighty grants us a non-violent universe. i canâ€™t think of anything else at the moment,â€ she said.

and she isnâ€™t bothered with what alok nath is doing. â€œthis piece of news about alok nath acting in a film is irrelevant and has no effect upon what is actually going on in my heart,â€ she said.

vinta had accused alok nath of allegedly raping her nearly 19 years ago when they worked together, which made for several such claims about his behaviour on the sets. he denied all the allegations levelled by the victim.

i will always and forever be proud to be a woman. i was taught since i was little â€œdonâ€™t be too loudâ€, â€œdonâ€™t talk too muchâ€, â€œdonâ€™t wear thisâ€, â€œthis isnâ€™t ladylikeâ€. these type of comments have made me a very insecure and a confused teenage girl that had to go against what my natural instincts have told me to do. i didnâ€™t know what to do in life, how to act around boys, how to express myself without being judged for who i am. 
it is extremely challenging to live in a world that is still run by those principles. 
if you are a young girl, please donâ€™t be afraid to speak up. nobody should be bringing you down if your heart and intentions are pure. i have been held back in life by men (and some women) that have shamed me into thinking that i was never enough, imperfect, loud, nosy, obnoxious, know it all, naive etc. bottom line is, be yourself, live for yourself. stay kind and pure and the universe will take care of the rest ğŸ’—

text:
san francisco giants team president and ceo larry baer apologized friday night after video earlier in the day showed him having an altercation with his wife during a fight over his cellphone at a san francisco park.
the incident was caught on video and published on tmz sports.
in the video, baer's wife, pam, screams, "oh, my god! no!" while falling to the ground as her husband attempts to take the cellphone from her. the video also shows larry baer holding that cellphone while walking away.
in a statement friday night, pam baer attempted to clarify what occurred. she said she took her husband's cellphone and did not want to give it back. when she attempted to get up from the chair in which she was sitting, she said it tipped and a previous foot injury caused her to lose her balance.
"i did not sustain any injury based on what happened today," she said. "larry and i always have been and still are happily married."
the couple previously expressed regret for what happened, saying in a joint statement that they are "deeply embarrassed by the situation and have resolved the issue.''

text:
spotted in berlin. 
are you serious, fun factory? referring to female hysteria and suggesting that a vibrator would be the perfect means to keep women from making trouble? because this is what the history of female hysteria is about: first, the uterus was believed to wander around the body like an animal, hungry for semen â€“ and only marriage, intercourse, and pregnancy was the ultimate treatment for this. the general belief was that â€œthe uterus was a troublemaker and was best sated when pregnantâ€, as terri kapsalis explains (https://lithub.com/hysteria-witches-and-the-wandering-uterus-a-brief-history/). later it was believed that hysteria could be caused by various bad habits like reading novels, masturbation, and homosexuality resulting in symptoms such as irrationality and general troublemaking. â€œit is no accident that such a diagnosis took off just as some of these same women were fighting to gain access to universities and various professions in the us and europeâ€, says kapsalis. either fun factory has no clue about the scope of this history, or, which is more likely, they very well know and want to make a tongue-in-cheek joke â€“ which is even worse. #shop #display #femalehysteria #sexistdesign #feminism #troublemaking
